diff:1670640523:1670340057:=61,77c61%0a%3c #foxbegin 221210-024843-372640#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Interpreting Non-English Songs in ASL %0a%3c -> - jackagui%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 18:48-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221210-024843-372640 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c My mom is a professional sign language interpreter, and has interpreted many concerts in the past, including some that had lyrics not in English. How the interpreting happens depends on the show. She interpreted a BTS concert, and the setup there was that there was a Korean-English translator who was speaking into a microphone that went into an earpiece that my mom then translated into ASL in real time. That was difficult as there was a delay from both the translation and the audio delay from the earpiece. For more recent concerts, she has the lyrics translated ahead of time, and tries to follow along in English as best as she can while the artists sing in Korean. Many K-pop songs include words or phrases in English, so it's possible to try to follow along with where you are in the song.%0a%3c %0a%3c Something to note is that translation of a song is rarely perfect, and generally does not capture all the nuances the interpreter may want to convey, as concerts are hours long, and it's one or two interpreters for the entire show. Between that and the wide range of concerts and artists that an interpreter has to translate for, it is near impossible for an interpreter to do everything perfectly.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221210-024843-372640#%0a---%0a> %0a
