cus on conveying the musicality of a song, which could be compromised of supersegmental characteristics of English. Interpreters will convey a song through their body movement, too, being more animated during faster songs and less during slower songs. "He translated the lyrics, 'We crawl, we crawl on the ground,' from 'Six Weeks,' with a snarling facial expression and slow, desperate clawing motions with his arms"[2]. Facial expressions are a visual element of ASL that isn't used the same way by English speakers, it's a unique semantic.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources%0a%3c [1] https://www.cpr.org/2019/07/23/sign-language-interpreter-concerts-red-rocks-colorado/%0a---%0a> [Note: All the articles I read were about interpreting English songs to ASL, so I only talk about this area of sign language interpreters at concerts.]%0a> %0a> I've been lucky enough to get to see a few concerts and almost every time I go they have a sign language interpreter. They're incredibly fascinating to watch perform (because at their level it truly is an additional performance along with the rest of the band), but I'm wondering, what's going on?%0a> %0a> In all the articles I read the idea that sign language is its own language was vital to explaining the work that interpreters must put into a performance. %0a> %0a> From what I've read it seems like ASL syntactically differs from English in that oftentimes the exact word-by-word English translation isn't expressed, but more of the idea. "Ahead of a concert, Austin will research an artist's top songs, and set lists from previous performances. She looks up the lyrics, and translates them into ASL. That’s a challenge because ASL is a distinct language with its own idioms, and its word order is different from English" [1].%0a> %0a> ASL differs from English in lexicon, too. Some words aren't sign-able except via letter forms (which would take too much time in a concert environment), or requires more of an in-group knowledge. "'Unfit for Human Consumption' by Carcass posed a major challenge for Sosebee, a[n interpreter]"[2] -- the song uses a ton of medical terminology that may not be recognized when signed. Of course, English-speaking audience members may not recognize a word like "lymphandetitis", but they may be able to understand its a diagnosis because it sounds like one. A compromise for a interpreter could be going for a "message-equivalent" translation instead of a "word-equivalent" translation; signing the purpose of the song over the exact words.%0a> %0a> While ASL language users have a range of hearing ability, interpreters still must focus on conveying the musicality of a song, which could be compromised of supersegmental characteristics of English. Interpreters will convey a song through their body movement, too, being more animated during faster songs and less during slower songs. "He translated the lyrics, 'We crawl, we crawl on the ground,' from 'Six Weeks,' with a snarling facial expression and slow, desperate clawing motions with his arms"[2]. Facial expressions are a visual element of ASL that isn't used the same way by English speakers, it's a unique semantic.%0a> %0a> Sources%0a> [1] https://www.cpr.org/2019/07/23/sign-language-interpreter-concerts-red-rocks-colorado/%0a95c95%0a%3c (:Category: SignLanguage:)%0a---%0a> (:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)%0a
